It just feels like

250
00:12:27,813 --> 00:12:29,749
you're like, you know,

251
00:12:29,815 --> 00:12:32,384
running from like, some kind of problem.

252
00:12:32,451 --> 00:12:33,619
You use "like" a lot.

253
00:12:34,186 --> 00:12:37,723
If I were a parent, I'd want to spend
as much time as possible with my kid.

254
00:12:38,824 --> 00:12:40,459
What would I do if I saw her?

255
00:12:40,526 --> 00:12:41,794
I can't tell her the truth.

256
00:12:41,861 --> 00:12:43,095
Why not?

257
00:12:43,162 --> 00:12:45,631
What good will that do?
I can't change the future!

258
00:12:45,698 --> 00:12:47,133
Why can't you?

259
00:12:47,199 --> 00:12:48,801
You can't do that.

260
00:12:50,936 --> 00:12:52,505
Since I arrived early,

261
00:12:53,005 --> 00:12:57,376
I asked him to give me a tour and explain
the principle of the time machine.

262
00:12:58,043 --> 00:12:59,779
I'm not concerned with the specifics.

263
00:12:59,845 --> 00:13:01,781
Just transport Ichiro to the past.

264
00:13:01,847 --> 00:13:03,916
Forget it. I don't want to go.

265
00:13:04,517 --> 00:13:06,685
This project has government recognition,

266
00:13:06,752 --> 00:13:09,922
but trial runs are currently
being conducted in secret.

267
00:13:10,422 --> 00:13:12,091
Only one bus runs on Saturday.

268
00:13:12,825 --> 00:13:13,826
Saturday?

269
00:13:14,660 --> 00:13:18,030
It leaves at 4:55 a.m.
and returns at 3:55 p.m.

270
00:13:18,831 --> 00:13:21,600
<i>My son added the times
to the timetable to remember them,</i>

271
00:13:21,667 --> 00:13:23,068
<i>and he hid it with tape.</i>

272
00:13:24,236 --> 00:13:25,104
Currently,

273
00:13:25,171 --> 00:13:28,207
<i>there are 50 passengers,
including my wife and son,</i>

274
00:13:28,274 --> 00:13:31,076
<i>registered on a face recognition system.</i>

275
00:13:31,143 --> 00:13:33,445
What? Then why was I able to
board the bus?

276
00:13:34,880 --> 00:13:36,182
That's because…

277
00:13:37,449 --> 00:13:40,920
when setting up
the facial recognition system,

278
00:13:41,453 --> 00:13:44,523
I used your photo as a sample.

279
00:13:59,138 --> 00:14:00,239
That's creepy.

280
00:14:00,306 --> 00:14:03,709
I was born with weak semicircular canals,

281
00:14:03,776 --> 00:14:07,146
and when I got on the bus,
my ears went "eeee."

282
00:14:07,213 --> 00:14:09,215
That's why I switched
to a self-driving bus.

283
00:14:09,782 --> 00:14:11,584
That explains the other passengers.

284
00:14:11,650 --> 00:14:13,385
Any other questions?

285
00:14:13,452 --> 00:14:16,989
Why did I fall into the bathroom
both times I returned to the past?

286
00:14:17,890 --> 00:14:18,724
That's because…

287
00:14:20,826 --> 00:14:21,827
I don't know.

288
00:14:22,394 --> 00:14:24,063
Why don't you know that?

289
00:14:27,199 --> 00:14:29,235
Did you know…

290
00:14:30,703 --> 00:14:31,971
that I'm going to die?

291
00:14:32,671 --> 00:14:33,806
Of course.

292
00:14:34,406 --> 00:14:37,042
I visit your grave every year.

293
00:14:37,643 --> 00:14:39,245
I'm in a grave, huh?

294
00:14:40,646 --> 00:14:41,881
You should've said, baldy.

295
00:14:43,382 --> 00:14:48,754
What if you stop Junko
from meeting the black suit at a disco…

296
00:14:48,821 --> 00:14:49,688
No way.

297
00:14:49,755 --> 00:14:52,024
Why not?
Both you and Junko will be able to live.

298
00:14:52,091 --> 00:14:53,659
Nagisacchi wouldn't exist!

299
00:15:08,741 --> 00:15:10,676
It's inevitable. It can't be helped.

300
00:15:11,410 --> 00:15:13,279
Dying isn't a negative event.

301
00:15:13,879 --> 00:15:17,683
Rather, having the chance to meet you
as an adult is a positive experience.

302
00:15:19,652 --> 00:15:22,021
I'm already dead, after all.

303
00:15:26,058 --> 00:15:26,992
Grandpa…

304
00:15:33,265 --> 00:15:36,435
I guess I'll go see your mom
after so long.

305
00:15:38,304 --> 00:15:40,339
Crap.

306
00:15:40,406 --> 00:15:42,274
Kiyoshi, wait!

307
00:15:42,841 --> 00:15:45,077
You forgot your rice balls!

308
00:15:45,144 --> 00:15:45,978
Hey!

309
00:15:46,045 --> 00:15:47,613
-Good morning.
-Good morning.

310
00:15:47,680 --> 00:15:48,847
Hey!

311
00:15:48,914 --> 00:15:50,616
-Morning.
-Morning.

312
00:15:50,683 --> 00:15:54,753
I spotted Yuki Matsumura
at a station in Kinshicho!

313
00:15:54,820 --> 00:15:56,755
No way! The Baddest Punk in Kawahama?

314
00:15:56,822 --> 00:15:57,656
Why was he there?

315
00:15:57,723 --> 00:15:59,658
He's probably shooting a new drama.

316
00:15:59,725 --> 00:16:00,926
Skip school?

317
00:16:00,993 --> 00:16:02,227
Definitely!

318
00:16:02,294 --> 00:16:03,195
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

319
00:16:07,266 --> 00:16:08,300
Junko.

320
00:16:11,170 --> 00:16:12,237
You're back.

321
00:16:14,440 --> 00:16:15,741
Where did you get that?

322
00:16:17,443 --> 00:16:18,477
It's custom-made.

323
00:16:21,213 --> 00:16:22,047
What do you think?

324
00:16:22,114 --> 00:16:23,983
ICHIRO OGAWA

325
00:16:25,017 --> 00:16:26,051
Pretty cool.

326
00:16:33,792 --> 00:16:34,660
Junko.

327
00:16:39,465 --> 00:16:40,532
Yeah.

328
00:16:41,900 --> 00:16:42,901
I'm back.

329
00:16:44,303 --> 00:16:45,571
I'm back, Junko.

330
00:16:47,072 --> 00:16:48,140
-Yeah.
-Yeah.

331
00:16:50,542 --> 00:16:52,611
Hey, my friends are watching.

332
00:16:58,784 --> 00:17:01,086
Take good care of Junko.

333
00:17:01,153 --> 00:17:02,888
Oh, okay.

334
00:17:07,359 --> 00:17:08,494
Too tight.

335
00:17:09,228 --> 00:17:10,462
Mr. Ogawa?

336
00:17:12,531 --> 00:17:13,432
What are you doing?

337
00:17:14,566 --> 00:17:15,601
Sakae.

338
00:17:16,502 --> 00:17:18,704
Thanks for looking after things
while I was gone.

339
00:17:18,771 --> 00:17:20,039
Whoa, hey!

340
00:17:20,105 --> 00:17:22,174
Stop. It's too early for that.

341
00:17:22,241 --> 00:17:23,075
What?!

342
00:17:30,182 --> 00:17:31,750
Mr. Ogawa, where have you been?

343
00:17:32,785 --> 00:17:33,919
Just somewhere else.

344
00:17:33,986 --> 00:17:35,054
-Mr. Principal!
-What?

345
00:17:35,120 --> 00:17:36,722
Check this out.

346
00:17:36,789 --> 00:17:38,290
-You wear it like this.
-What? No.

347
00:17:38,357 --> 00:17:39,224
There you go.

348
00:17:39,291 --> 00:17:40,826
Huh? Hey.

349
00:17:40,893 --> 00:17:42,694
-What's this?
-You've caused us trouble.

350
00:17:42,761 --> 00:17:45,264
Even as an assistant,
you can't just be absent without--

351
00:17:45,330 --> 00:17:48,534
Now, Mr. Yasumori,
you're a Hanshin fan, aren't you?

352
00:17:48,600 --> 00:17:51,737
This is an Okada mug commemorating
their victory after 38 years.

353
00:17:52,471 --> 00:17:53,872
After 38 years?

354
00:17:53,939 --> 00:17:55,541
What do you mean, 38 years?

355
00:17:55,607 --> 00:17:57,009
What is this?

356
00:17:57,076 --> 00:17:59,144
Women! I see women!

357
00:17:59,211 --> 00:18:00,479
Huh?

358
00:18:02,748 --> 00:18:05,350
Eat up. Eat more, Junko!

359
00:18:05,851 --> 00:18:08,220
I feel a little bad
for joining you for dinner.

360
00:18:08,787 --> 00:18:11,757
We're going to have a lot to do
with each other ahead.

361
00:18:12,324 --> 00:18:13,459
Right.

362
00:18:13,525 --> 00:18:14,393
Is that so?

363
00:18:15,027 --> 00:18:17,329
Maybe you're my future husband.

364
00:18:20,532 --> 00:18:22,935
Huh? Is he really?

365
00:18:23,502 --> 00:18:24,837
Never mind. Just eat.

366
00:18:24,903 --> 00:18:26,972
Forget the leeks.
Eat the meat two slices at a time!

367
00:18:27,840 --> 00:18:30,042
Do people in the future eat sukiyaki too?

368
00:18:30,109 --> 00:18:31,777
We mostly eat the same stuff.

369
00:18:31,844 --> 00:18:33,512
The saury gets smaller, though.

370
00:18:36,415 --> 00:18:37,716
Hmm.

371
00:18:37,783 --> 00:18:39,985
What's with the "hmm."

372
00:18:40,819 --> 00:18:41,887
Something seems off.

373
00:18:42,821 --> 00:18:44,590
You didn't go to the future, did you?

374
00:18:45,958 --> 00:18:46,959
Sorry.

375
00:18:47,459 --> 00:18:50,129
I've been feeling like I'm not keeping up.

376
00:18:50,195 --> 00:18:51,063
With what?

377
00:18:51,130 --> 00:18:53,699
With the conversation
about the future and stuff.

378
00:18:55,200 --> 00:18:58,470
Should I take all of this
with a grain of salt?

379
00:19:00,639 --> 00:19:02,574
How about another egg?

380
00:19:02,641 --> 00:19:03,709
Yes, please.

381
00:19:06,278 --> 00:19:08,313
You were in Susukino, weren't you?

382
00:19:08,380 --> 00:19:10,015
Junko!

383
00:19:10,582 --> 00:19:13,819
I can explain.
I had a spat with my wife in the past.

384
00:19:14,386 --> 00:19:17,189
When Junko was still a kid,
she had a fever and was crying.

385
00:19:17,256 --> 00:19:20,325
But I was sitting there,
watching an <i>11 PM</i> special on Susukino.

386
00:19:20,392 --> 00:19:21,493
And I failed to notice.

387
00:19:23,829 --> 00:19:25,697
I'm surprised you remember.

388
00:19:25,764 --> 00:19:27,432
Don't dodge the question.

389
00:19:28,534 --> 00:19:29,735
You're lying to me.

390
00:19:29,801 --> 00:19:31,670
Do you have any proof?

391
00:19:31,737 --> 00:19:34,139
Tell us something surprising
about the future,

392
00:19:34,206 --> 00:19:35,841
if you really did go to the future.

393
00:19:36,408 --> 00:19:39,511
Tell me what it's like
38 years down the road.

394
00:19:45,784 --> 00:19:47,719
Junko Mihara becomes a Diet member.

395
00:19:48,287 --> 00:19:49,121
What?!

396
00:19:49,188 --> 00:19:50,556
That's a lie!

397
00:19:50,622 --> 00:19:52,157
It's true. She's an active politician.

398
00:19:52,724 --> 00:19:54,159
You expect us to believe that?

399
00:19:54,693 --> 00:19:58,397
She's Reiko Yamada,
the queen of hussies, our role model.

400
00:19:58,463 --> 00:20:01,099
She's famous for saying,
"Not the face, focus on his body."

401
00:20:01,166 --> 00:20:03,435
And she's in politics now? Unbelievable.

402
00:20:03,502 --> 00:20:05,771
She's confusing reality with <i>Mr. Kinpachi</i>.

403
00:20:05,837 --> 00:20:06,872
I've got one more.

404
00:20:07,372 --> 00:20:08,640
You'll be astonished.

405
00:20:10,042 --> 00:20:11,243
Kato-chan

406
00:20:12,177 --> 00:20:14,513
at the age of 80, has a wife who's 35.

407
00:20:15,080 --> 00:20:16,315
What?!

408
00:20:16,381 --> 00:20:18,217
Are you kidding me?

409
00:20:18,283 --> 00:20:20,686
If his wife is 35 in 38 years,

410
00:20:21,186 --> 00:20:22,554
she hasn't even been born!

411
00:20:22,621 --> 00:20:24,489
That's scary! It's like a sci-fi story!

412
00:20:25,057 --> 00:20:26,091
Kin-chan is 82.

413
00:20:27,259 --> 00:20:29,561
He drops out of university when he's 78.

414
00:20:29,628 --> 00:20:31,263
Stop. The fabric of time and space…

415
00:20:31,830 --> 00:20:32,831
It's unraveling!

416
00:20:34,266 --> 00:20:35,767
What about Matchy? Our idol?

417
00:20:38,003 --> 00:20:40,005
After a series of events,
he becomes a racer.

418
00:20:41,006 --> 00:20:42,641
That's our Matchy!

419
00:21:07,766 --> 00:21:08,767
I'm sorry.

420
00:21:09,868 --> 00:21:11,470
I don't know what to say.

421
00:21:14,106 --> 00:21:15,340
I don't care about myself.

422
00:21:16,308 --> 00:21:17,643
I can die whenever.

423
00:21:20,312 --> 00:21:21,680
But not Junko.

424
00:21:24,516 --> 00:21:26,285
To think she only has 26 years to live.

425
00:21:30,122 --> 00:21:31,456
It's too short.

426
00:21:32,424 --> 00:21:33,759
No matter how you look at it.

427
00:21:46,271 --> 00:21:47,572
Totally.

428
00:21:50,275 --> 00:21:52,010
My wife was often sick,

429
00:21:53,745 --> 00:21:55,914
so I took special care of Junko's health.

430
00:21:58,250 --> 00:22:00,218
But all that effort will be wasted.
Damn it.

431
00:22:06,224 --> 00:22:08,360
If you know how your life will play out,

432
00:22:10,729 --> 00:22:12,397
is there even a point in living?

433
00:22:26,611 --> 00:22:27,879
It can't be helped.

434
00:22:29,047 --> 00:22:30,349
Not this.

435
00:22:34,786 --> 00:22:35,887
Sorry.

436
00:22:38,824 --> 00:22:41,493
You're about the only one I can talk to.

437
00:22:46,131 --> 00:22:47,165
So…

438
00:22:48,066 --> 00:22:49,434
what are you going to do?

439
00:22:53,772 --> 00:22:55,073
What would you do?

440
00:22:56,274 --> 00:22:59,978
If you knew that your son
only had nine years left to live,

441
00:23:01,747 --> 00:23:02,848
would you tell him?

442
00:23:07,753 --> 00:23:11,123
If there's no way to change his fate,
there's no use in telling him.

443
00:23:13,925 --> 00:23:16,561
That would be
my line of thinking, I think.

444
00:23:20,665 --> 00:23:23,235
Is it really inevitable?

445
00:23:36,348 --> 00:23:39,384
Up to the point that Nagisa is born,

446
00:23:40,352 --> 00:23:42,788
Junko's life isn't bad.

447
00:23:43,388 --> 00:23:44,489
It's wonderful, in fact.

448
00:23:48,126 --> 00:23:49,327
We're all smiles,

449
00:23:50,362 --> 00:23:51,630
Junko and I.

450
00:23:54,366 --> 00:23:56,301
The problem is what comes next.

451
00:23:58,069 --> 00:23:59,137
I know…

452
00:24:01,606 --> 00:24:03,308
what happens after this.

453
00:24:06,244 --> 00:24:07,879
And yet, I can't…

454
00:24:19,324 --> 00:24:21,593
Maybe you're supposed to worry about it

455
00:24:22,360 --> 00:24:23,728
when that moment comes.

456
00:24:27,232 --> 00:24:28,867
If the situation will stay the same

457
00:24:29,601 --> 00:24:32,037
whether you fret about it now or later,

458
00:24:33,104 --> 00:24:34,906
maybe it's best to enjoy the present

459
00:24:36,475 --> 00:24:38,243
and live life the way you want to.

460
00:24:57,128 --> 00:24:58,096
You're right.

461
00:24:59,531 --> 00:25:00,899
It's not happening right away.

462
00:25:03,201 --> 00:25:05,337
We still have nine years ahead of us.

463
00:25:07,772 --> 00:25:09,241
Nine years left to live.

464
00:25:17,983 --> 00:25:18,817
You…

465
00:25:22,854 --> 00:25:23,755
You were here?

466
00:25:23,822 --> 00:25:25,223
Why did you think I was gone?

467
00:25:25,790 --> 00:25:27,826
Quiet! Come over here.

468
00:25:29,728 --> 00:25:32,931
My stomach hurt because I ate too much.

469
00:25:33,498 --> 00:25:34,766
So, I was using the bathroom

470
00:25:34,833 --> 00:25:37,302
when you guys, like,
started this serious conversation.

471
00:25:38,069 --> 00:25:41,306
And it was like, I didn't even exist,

472
00:25:41,873 --> 00:25:43,708
and I couldn't like, step out.

473
00:25:43,775 --> 00:25:45,210
You sure use "like" a lot.

474
00:25:45,277 --> 00:25:47,212
I'm not the type of guy
to leave without a word.

475
00:25:50,949 --> 00:25:54,152
I always make sure to say
thank you before I leave.

476
00:25:54,219 --> 00:25:56,655
-I've got decency.
-Sorry about that.

477
00:25:56,721 --> 00:25:57,822
Take care on your way home.

478
00:25:57,889 --> 00:25:59,024
Hey.

479
00:25:59,524 --> 00:26:01,626
Is Junko going to die?

480
00:26:01,693 --> 00:26:02,794
Let's step outside.

481
00:26:02,861 --> 00:26:04,362
Come on.

482
00:26:10,402 --> 00:26:12,270
What's going on? Is something the matter?

483
00:26:12,837 --> 00:26:13,805
Huh?

484
00:26:13,872 --> 00:26:15,807
Nothing. Go back to sleep.

485
00:26:16,308 --> 00:26:18,710
-Junko. Is Junko going to die?
-Listen, Akitsu. Hey!

486
00:26:18,777 --> 00:26:20,645
Calm down. Listen to me.

487
00:26:21,880 --> 00:26:22,714
That was

488
00:26:23,214 --> 00:26:24,149
all an act.

489
00:26:25,183 --> 00:26:26,117
An act?

490
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:27,319
Yes, just an act.

491
00:26:28,320 --> 00:26:29,955
We lied for you to hear,

492
00:26:30,455 --> 00:26:32,490
to make a man out of you.

493
00:26:33,391 --> 00:26:34,359
To make

494
00:26:34,859 --> 00:26:36,394
a man out of me?

495
00:26:36,461 --> 00:26:37,295
That's right.

496
00:26:39,898 --> 00:26:43,401
Junko is experiencing
the frogification phenomenon right now.

497
00:26:43,969 --> 00:26:45,937
Junko is turning into a frog?

498
00:26:47,072 --> 00:26:48,840
It's when you lose interest in your crush

499
00:26:48,907 --> 00:26:51,710
the moment
they start paying attention to you.

500
00:26:51,776 --> 00:26:53,211
Girls are like that.

501
00:26:53,712 --> 00:26:54,646
So,

502
00:26:55,547 --> 00:26:57,549
it's best to distance yourself for now

503
00:26:58,650 --> 00:27:00,218
and make her feel anxious.

504
00:27:03,188 --> 00:27:04,823
I don't…

505
00:27:06,424 --> 00:27:08,026
dislike doing that sort of thing.

506
00:27:08,093 --> 00:27:09,928
-Good.
-Yeah.

507
00:27:12,764 --> 00:27:13,865
-Hey.
-Huh?

508
00:27:14,499 --> 00:27:16,735
How was Yasuko Sawaguchi?

509
00:27:19,304 --> 00:27:20,572
She was working for S.R.I.

510
00:27:22,040 --> 00:27:23,174
What about Yuki Saito?

511
00:27:23,742 --> 00:27:25,477
She was in the investigation division.

512
00:27:25,543 --> 00:27:26,678
The delinquent detective?

513
00:27:27,312 --> 00:27:28,146
Cool.

514
00:27:29,347 --> 00:27:30,315
What about me?

515
00:27:30,949 --> 00:27:31,850
What?

516
00:27:32,717 --> 00:27:34,452
Never mind. I don't want to know.

517
00:27:35,053 --> 00:27:36,621
I want to keep it a surprise.

518
00:27:41,226 --> 00:27:42,494
